            No Captiuity beyond the Graue; and no word in this Chapter to set out this Captiuitie, but is translated from a Graue: Shew me, O sonne of Man, the value of dead and drie Bones, Sinewes, and Flesh brought vpon these Bones; Breath fetcht from the foure Winds to animate these Bones: Ossa haec vniuersa domus Israel est, These Bones are the whole House of Israel; nay, the whole House of the whole world must become as these Bones, Dry and Marrowlesse, diuested of Flesh and Sinewes, and lay'd for a time in such a lasting Sleepe, where they shall not so much as dreame of this their Lord. But, euen then, that Eye of his, which neither slumbers nor sleepes, will keepe a watch ouer them: And those that vpon the heauie wings of Death, goe to the vttermost parts of the Earth, shall there finde him and his power in opening of Graues.
            
